3.1   Thermal Cross Sections                                      4028 1451
----------------------------                                      4028 1451
                                                                  4028 1451
    The thermal cross sections were in evaluated December 2010    4028 1451
by S.F. Mughabghab (BNL) using two bound levels to describe the   4028 1451
thermal capture cross section and bound coherent and incoherent   4028 1451
scattering lengths [4]. A value of the thermal capture cross      4028 1451
section, 1.216 b, was derived from the natural element and        4028 1451
isotopic capture cross sections by the subtraction method. This   4028 1451
value is consistent within two standard deviations from the one   4028 1451
measured recently by Nakamura et al. [8].                         4028 1451
                                                                  4028 1451
                                                                  4028 1451
3.2  Resolved Resonance Parameters In MLBW                        4028 1451
------------------------------------------                        4028 1451
                                                                  4028 1451
    We also adopted resonance parameters below 20 keV and an      4028 1451
effective scattering radius of 7.2 fm from Mughabghab [4]. We     4028 1451
assume average radiative widths of 127 meV and 223 meV for those  4028 1451
s- and p-wave resonances, respectively, for whose widths were     4028 1451
not determined from measurements [5, 6, 4]. We assigned ell       4028 1451
values that had not been determined from measurements by          4028 1451
applying the Bayesian approach while undetermined J values were   4028 1451
assigned randomly to follow the 2J+1 rule. With these             4028 1451
parameters, we compute the Wescott factor for capture as g_w =    4028 1451
1.0031.                                                           4028 1451
